  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize knowingly conducting financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n- Impose penalties and fines for violations\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Potential Penalties:\n- Significant fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Civil and criminal sanctions\n\n5. State-Level Laws:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to help track and prosecute financial crimes.",
